#compdef content-collections
# =============================================================================
# content-collections — Transform your content into type-safe data collections.
#                       A build-time content management library that reads
#                       Markdown / MDX / JSON / YAML / TypeScript files from
#                       a content directory, validates them with Zod schemas,
#                       and emits typed JavaScript modules ready to import
#                       from Next.js / Astro / SvelteKit / Vite / Webpack
#                       applications.  Used as a lightweight alternative to
#                       Contentlayer (now deprecated) for type-safe content
#                       in static-site frameworks.
#
# Author:  Sebastian Sdorra (sdorra)
# Source:  https://github.com/sdorra/content-collections
# CLI:     packages/cli/src/index.ts (uses @clerc/core)
# Library: clercjs/clerc
#          ("🖖🏻 Clerc: The full-featured cli library")
# License: MIT
# Status:  Active — 1,156+ stars; recommended replacement for Contentlayer
#          across Next.js/Astro/SvelteKit content-driven sites since
#          Contentlayer's maintenance pause in 2024.
#
# -----------------------------------------------------------------------------
# CROSS-LANGUAGE CLI LIBRARY TAXONOMY MILESTONE — TS-NODE CROSSES TO 31
# -----------------------------------------------------------------------------
# With this completion the cross-language CLI library taxonomy documents the
# 31ST TypeScript-Node CLI library variant.  TypeScript-Node climbs from
# 30 to 31 documented libraries (clerc via content-collections).  New
# leaderboard: Rust=31, Go=31, TypeScript-Node=31 — THREE-WAY TIE RESTORED
# at the 31-variant level.  Taxonomy now spans 235 cross-language CLI
# library variants across 56 documented languages.
# -----------------------------------------------------------------------------
#
# WHAT IS clercjs/clerc AND WHY IS IT A DISTINCT 31ST TS-NODE CLI LIBRARY?
#
# clerc (https://github.com/clercjs/clerc, 222+ stars) is the **"full-
# featured CLI library"** by the clercjs organization (lead author so1ve).
# Built on top of privatenumber's type-flag (the low-level typed argv
# parser), clerc adds a PLUGIN ARCHITECTURE, FLUENT BUILDER API, and
# EVENT-BASED HANDLER ATTACHMENT — positioning itself between the
# minimalism of cleye R472 / type-flag and the framework-heaviness of
# oclif R492.
#
# clerc is DISTINCT from every documented TS-Node CLI library on SIX
# specific axes:
#
#   1. EVENT-BASED HANDLER ATTACHMENT — clerc separates COMMAND
#      REGISTRATION from HANDLER ATTACHMENT.  You first declare the
#      command's schema with `.command(name, description, { flags })`,
#      then attach handlers via `.on(commandName, handler)`:
#         Clerc.create()
#             .command("build", "Build collections", {
#                 flags: { config: { type: String, default: "..." } }
#             })
#             .on("build", (context) => {
#                 return build(context.flags.config);
#             })
#      No other documented TS-Node CLI library uses event-emitter-style
#      handler attachment.  Most attach handlers inline (commander.js
#      `.action()`, yargs `.handler()`, cleye R472 in command factory,
#      citty R476 `run` field).  clerc's separation lets multiple
#      handlers be attached to the same command (event-emitter
#      semantics) — useful for telemetry/logging hooks.
#
#   2. PLUGIN ARCHITECTURE VIA `.use()` — clerc has a first-class
#      plugin system that rivals oclif's R492 but with cleaner
#      functional composition.  Plugins are functions that mutate the
#      Cli instance:
#         Clerc.create()
#             .use(helpPlugin())
#             .use(versionPlugin())
#             .use(completionsPlugin())
#             .use(updateNotifierPlugin({ pkg }))
#             .use(notFoundPlugin())
#             .use(strictFlagsPlugin())
#             .use(friendlyErrorPlugin())
#      Official plugins ship as separate npm packages under @clerc/*.
#      Compare oclif's plugins (heavyweight, lazy-loaded, require oclif
#      runtime), clerc's plugins (lightweight, eagerly composed,
#      drop-in functions).
#
#   3. TYPE-FLAG UNDERLYING PARSER — clerc uses privatenumber's
#      type-flag library for the actual argv parsing.  This gives clerc
#      the same JS-type-constructor schema style as cleye R472 (which
#      also uses type-flag) — `{ type: String, default: "..." }`.  But
#      clerc adds the higher-level event/plugin layer that cleye lacks.
#      Documenting clerc as a SEPARATE entry from cleye is justified
#      because the user-facing API surface (events, plugins, fluent
#      chain) is fundamentally different even though they share an
#      underlying parser.
#
#   4. `.scriptName()` SEPARATE FROM CONSTRUCTOR — clerc's constructor
#      takes name + description + version inline:
#         Clerc.create("my-cli", "v1.0.0", "Description")
#      But you can ALSO call `.scriptName(name)` later to override.
#      content-collections uses `.scriptName(name)` after `Clerc.create()`
#      to pull the name from package.json at runtime rather than
#      hardcoding it.  This is a small ergonomic improvement over
#      libraries that fix the name at constructor time.
#
#   5. CONTEXT OBJECT WITH `flags` AND `unknownFlags` — clerc's handler
#      receives a `context` object:
#         .on("build", (context) => {
#             const config = context.flags.config;
#             const unknown = context.unknownFlags;  // strict-flags plugin
#             const parameters = context.parameters; // positional args
#         })
#      The Context exposes parsed flags, positional arguments, the raw
#      argv, and (with plugins) unknown-flag detection.  More structured
#      than commander.js's `(options, command)` callback or yargs's
#      `argv` object.
#
#   6. SCOPED npm PACKAGES — clerc is distributed as a constellation of
#      @clerc/* packages:
#         @clerc/core — the main parser + builder
#         @clerc/plugin-help — help text generation
#         @clerc/plugin-version — version flag
#         @clerc/plugin-completions — bash/zsh/fish completions
#         @clerc/plugin-not-found — better unknown-command errors
#         @clerc/plugin-strict-flags — reject unknown flags
#         @clerc/plugin-friendly-error — pretty error messages
#         @clerc/plugin-update-notifier — npm update notifications
#         @clerc/test-utils — testing helpers
#      Plus a `clerc` umbrella package that re-exports `@clerc/core` for
#      convenience.  This @scoped-namespace distribution lets users
#      install only the plugins they need without bloating the
#      dependency tree.
#
# THE clerc API SURFACE (verbatim from content-collections usage)
#
#   import { Clerc } from "@clerc/core";
#   import { completionsPlugin } from "@clerc/plugin-completions";
#   import { helpPlugin } from "@clerc/plugin-help";
#   import { versionPlugin } from "@clerc/plugin-version";
#
#   Clerc.create()
#       .scriptName("content-collections")
#       .description("Transform content into type-safe collections")
#       .version("1.0.0")
#       .command("build", "Build collections", {
#           flags: {
#               config: {
#                   type: String,
#                   description: "Path to config file",
#                   default: "content-collections.ts",
#               },
#           },
#       })
#       .on("build", (context) => {
#           return build(context.flags.config);
#       })
#       .command("watch", "Build and watch for changes", {
#           flags: {
#               config: { type: String, default: "..." },
#           },
#       })
#       .on("watch", async (context) => {
#           return watch(context.flags.config);
#       })
#       .use(helpPlugin())
#       .use(versionPlugin())
#       .use(completionsPlugin())
#       .parse();
#
# Common Cli methods:
#   Clerc.create(name?, version?, description?)
#   .scriptName(name)
#   .description(desc)
#   .version(version)
#   .command(name, description, { flags, parameters })
#   .on(commandName, handler)
#   .use(plugin)
#   .parse(argv?)
#   .interceptor(name, fn) — middleware-style interceptors
#
# Flag schema:
#   { type: String, default: "...", description: "...", alias: "x" }
#   { type: Number, default: 0, ... }
#   { type: Boolean, default: false, ... }
#   { type: [String], default: [], ... } — array variants
#
# CONTRAST WITH OTHER TS-NODE CLI LIBRARIES DOCUMENTED IN THE CORPUS
#
#   * commander.js (fluent), yargs (chainable), minimist (pure),
#     arg (small), meow (yargs wrap), mri (minimist successor), caporal,
#     nopt, cmd-ts, clipanion R480 (class+decorator), citty R476
#     (defineCommand UnJS), cac (chainable typed), sade (lukeed),
#     type-flag (the privatenumber low-level — clerc and cleye built on
#                it), vorpal R442 (REPL), gluegun (full framework),
#     stricli R466 (Bloomberg zero-dep), cleye R472 (TS-first by
#                                                  privatenumber, uses
#                                                  type-flag like clerc),
#     command-line-args R484 (UNIX-decomposed), cliffy R488 (Deno-first),
#     oclif R492 (enterprise framework with plugins), clerc (THIS,
#                                                            mid-layer
#                                                            with event-
#                                                            based handlers
#                                                            and lightweight
#                                                            plugins)
#
# clerc occupies a NICHE BETWEEN cleye R472 (minimal, no plugins, no
# events) and oclif R492 (heavyweight framework with scaffolding,
# autoload, manifest caching).  Where cleye says "give me a parser,"
# clerc says "give me a framework that's lighter than oclif but more
# capable than cleye."  Its event-based handlers + lightweight plugin
# composition make it uniquely positioned.
#
# REAL-WORLD clerc USERS:
#
#   * sdorra/content-collections — content management for Next.js/Astro
#                                   (THIS, 1156*)
#   * vue-vine/vue-vine — alternative Vue components syntax (1444*)
#   * versia-pub/server — Versia federation server (Mastodon-alt)
#   * Jaid/tldw — README generator from package.json + source
#   * simse/stamp — Git test-patch embed tool
#   * popcall-inc/ios-pwa-splash-gen — iOS PWA splash screen generator
#   * tennysontbardwell/tennyson.ts — personal scripts toolkit
#   * sleb/overdrip — overdrip CLI
#   * so1ve/tikko — project helper (by clerc's lead author)
#   * Many other Node.js CLIs from the clercjs-aware community
#
# -----------------------------------------------------------------------------
# CONTENT-COLLECTIONS'S CLI SURFACE (verbatim from packages/cli/src/index.ts)
# -----------------------------------------------------------------------------
#
# USAGE:
#   content-collections <COMMAND> [OPTIONS]
#
# Commands:
#   build                     Build collections (one-shot)
#                             Reads content directory, validates with Zod
#                             schemas, writes typed JS modules to .content-
#                             collections directory.
#
#   watch                     Build collections + watch for changes
#                             Same as build, but reruns on file changes
#                             via chokidar.
#
#   help                      Show help (from @clerc/plugin-help)
#   --version, -v             Show version (from @clerc/plugin-version)
#   completions               Generate shell completions
#                             (from @clerc/plugin-completions)
#
# Common flags (both build and watch):
#   --config <FILE>           Path to config file
#                             (default: content-collections.ts)
#
# Typical workflow:
#   $ content-collections build                  # one-shot build
#   $ content-collections watch                  # dev mode with auto-rebuild
#   $ content-collections build --config a.ts    # alternate config
#
# Configuration file (content-collections.ts):
#   import { defineCollection, defineConfig } from "@content-collections/core";
#   const posts = defineCollection({
#       name: "posts",
#       directory: "content/posts",
#       include: "**/*.md",
#       schema: (z) => ({
#           title: z.string(),
#           date: z.coerce.date(),
#       }),
#   });
#   export default defineConfig({ collections: [posts] });
#
# Output: .content-collections/generated/index.ts with typed `allPosts`,
# `allTags`, etc. exports.
#
# =============================================================================

_content-collections() {
    local curcontext="$curcontext" state line ret=1
    typeset -A opt_args

    local -a subcommands

    subcommands=(
        'build:build collections (one-shot)'
        'watch:build collections and watch for changes'
        'help:show help'
        'completions:generate shell completions'
    )

    _arguments -C \
        '(-v --version)'{-v,--version}'[show version]' \
        '(-h --help)'{-h,--help}'[show help]' \
        '1: :->cmd' \
        '*::arg:->args' && ret=0

    case $state in
        (cmd)
            _describe -t subcommands 'content-collections command' subcommands && ret=0
            ;;
        (args)
            case $line[1] in
                (build|watch)
                    _arguments \
                        '--config[path to config file]:config:_files -g "*.(ts|js|mjs)"' \
                        && ret=0
                    ;;
                (completions)
                    _values 'shell' bash zsh fish && ret=0
                    ;;
            esac
            ;;
    esac

    return ret
}

_content-collections "$@"
